Kanban and Gantt charts are extremely useful tools for visualizing a project or workflow. They provide visual representations of work items, their current status, and the workflow at different stages of the work. This makes it easy to identify bottlenecks, prioritize work, and improve process efficiency. Kanban and Gantt charts are practical and effective for managing agile projects, software development, and other continuous improvement processes.
It allows entering the details of the Kanban task. Kanban is a detailed required field.
It enables the selection of users to be assigned to the Kanban task. At least one user is required to be assigned to the kanban.
Allows you to select the start date of the Kanban task. In Kanban, the start date automatically takes the creation time of the task.
It allows to select the end date of the Kanban task. In Kanban, the task due date is automatically one week after the task creation time.
It allows to select the priority status of the Kanban task. In Kanban, the task due date is automatically one week after the task creation time.
It allows adding the tags of the Kanban task. Tags are separated from each other as they are added with commas.

This is the field used for groups that are not assigned to a task but are requested to have information. Persons belonging to groups added to inform cannot act on tasks.

It is used to indicate the progress of the Kanban task. Progress can be viewed on the Gantt chart.
